2026-05-10 | Maximum Profit by Assigning Tasks to Two Machines

Question
Return maximum possible profit.
	Key Insight
For every task:
		difference = |a[i] - b[i]|  
A larger difference means:
		that task strongly prefers one machine  
So:
		process tasks with larger differences first.
	Approach
1.	Create tasks with:
		(abs(a[i]-b[i]), a[i], b[i])
2.	Sort in descending order of difference  
3.	For each task:
		if A profit > B profit:
			assign to A if possible
			else B  
		else:
			assign to B if possible
			else A  
4.	Add profits accordingly  
	Time Complexity
	O(n log n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int maxProfit(vector<int>& a, vector<int>& b, int x, int y) {
        int n = a.size();
        vector<tuple<int,int,int>> tasks;
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            tasks.push_back({
                abs(a[i] - b[i]),
                a[i],
                b[i]
            });
        }
        sort(tasks.rbegin(), tasks.rend());
        int profit = 0;
        for(auto &[diff, pa, pb] : tasks){
            if((pa >= pb && x > 0) || y == 0){
                profit += pa;
                x--;
            }
            else{
                profit += pb;
                y--;
            }
        }
        return profit;
    }
};
	Key Insight
Tasks with bigger profit differences are more important:
		assign them first optimally  
This greedy strategy guarantees:
		maximum total profit.
